    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When things get messy, the escrow company acts as the referee, ensuring that the rules of the game are followed. If there's a disagreement or an issue with the house inspection, the escrow company will hold onto the funds until the problem is resolved.\n\nHere's how it typically works:\n\n1. Dispute Resolution: If there's a disagreement, such as a disagreement over the condition of the house or the terms of the sale, the parties involved will usually try to resolve the issue through negotiation or mediation. The escrow company may facilitate this process by providing a platform for communication.\n\n2. Inspection Contingencies: If the house inspection reveals problems that need to be addressed, the escrow company will hold onto the funds until those issues are resolved. This could involve the seller making repairs or the buyer agreeing to accept the house \"as is.\"\n\n3. Escrow Holdback: In some cases, the escrow company may release a portion of the funds to the seller as a holdback, which is a form of security for the buyer. This holdback is released only when the buyer is satisfied with the resolution of any issues or when the closing date arrives.\n\n4. Release of Funds: Once all disputes are resolved, and the buyer is satisfied with the condition of the house",
